    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's get straight to the technical details.\n\nTo systematically find the memory leak in your embedded C++ project, you can use Valgrind or AddressSanitizer (ASan). Both tools are designed to detect memory leaks, buffer overflows, and other memory-related issues.\n\nFor Valgrind, you can run your application with the following command:\n\n```bash\nvalgrind --leak-check=full --show-leak-kinds=all --track-origins=yes ./your_application\n```\n\nThis command will run your application under Valgrind's supervision, checking for memory leaks and providing detailed information about them. The `--leak-check=full` option enables a comprehensive leak check, while `--show-leak-kinds=all` displays all types of leaks. The `--track-origins=yes` option helps you trace the source of the leaks.\n\nFor AddressSanitizer, you can compile your code with the `-fsanitize=address` flag and run it as follows:\n\n```bash\nclang -fsanitize=address -g -o your_application your_application.cpp\n./your_application\n```\n\nASan will automatically detect memory leaks and other memory-related issues during runtime",
      "source": "target",
